Damped Newton‚Äôs Method: in order to Stabilize Newton‚Äôs method, we incorporate a 
step size of t. The update step is given as follows : 

wt+1 
= wt ‚àí tH‚àí1(wt)rf(wt) (8.16) 
Algorithm : The algorithm for (Damped) Newton‚Äôs method is given below : 

1. Initialize : w0. 
2. Update : wt+1 
= wt ‚àí tH‚àí1(wt)rf(wt). 
3. Iterate : Until some condition is met (kwt+1 
‚àí wtk ). If not, go to Update 
step. 
Advantages and Disadvantages : 

‚Ä¢ Convergence : Newton‚Äôs method usually gives a much faster convergence (in terms 
of the number of iterations) compared to the gradient descent method. However, each 
iteration of Newton‚Äôs method is more costly than that of the gradient descent method. 
Specifically, gradient descent update takes O (d) time and space because we need to 
manipulate d‚àídimensional vectors and gradients. However, Newton‚Äôs method involves 
calculation of inverse of Hessian, which requires O (d2) space and takes O (d3) time. 
Thus, there is a trade-off in number of iterations till convergence versus the complexity 
of each iteration. 
‚Ä¢ Affine Invariance and Role of H‚àí1: Newton‚Äôs method is Affine Invariant, which 
means that it is invariant to the re-scaling of variables. The reason behind this is that 
the update term of Newton‚Äôs method has the inverse of Hessian, which transforms 
the space to make it ‚Äúwell-conditioned‚Äù. We demonstrate the intuitive benefits of this 
property and the effect of the presence of Hessian-inverse in the following (optional) 
subsection. 
The Role of H‚àí1 
[Optional] : We consider a very simple example, where we have w 
